"MacDonald G.M., Kremenetski K.V., Beilman D.W.","Climate change and the northern Russian treeline zone",2008,"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","363","1501",,"2285","2299",,,10.1098/rstb.2007.2200,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-44449129012&partnerID=40&md5=3085098e1fe4c950631fc2a9064d5f3d","Department of Geography, University of California-Los Angeles, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1524, United States","MacDonald, G.M., Department of Geography, University of California-Los Angeles, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1524, United States; Kremenetski, K.V., Department of Geography, University of California-Los Angeles, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1524, United States; Beilman, D.W., Department of Geography, University of California-Los Angeles, Los Angeles, CA 90095-1524, United States","The Russian treeline is a dynamic ecotone typified by steep gradients in summer temperature and regionally variable gradients in albedo and heat flux. The location of the treeline is largely controlled by summer temperatures and growing season length. Temperatures have responded strongly to twentieth-century global warming and will display a magnified response to future warming. Dendroecological studies indicate enhanced conifer recruitment during the twentieth century. However, conifers have not yet recolonized many areas where trees were present during the Medieval Warm period (ca AD 800-1300) or the Holocene Thermal Maximum (HTM; ca 10000-3000 years ago). Reconstruction of tree distributions during the HTM suggests that the future position of the treeline due to global warming may approximate its former Holocene maximum position. An increased dominance of evergreen tree species in the northern Siberian forests may be an important difference between past and future conditions. Based on the slow rates of treeline expansion observed during the twentieth century, the presence of steep climatic gradients associated with the current Arctic coastline and the prevalence of organic soils, it is possible that rates of treeline expansion will be regionally variable and transient forest communities with species abundances different from today's may develop. © 2007 The Royal Society.","Arctic; Boreal forest; Climate change; Eurasia; Holocene; Treeline","albedo; arctic environment; boreal forest; coniferous forest; dendroecology; dominance; ecotone; evergreen tree; global warming; growing season; heat flux; Holocene; Medieval Warm Period; organic soil; reconstruction; recruitment (population dynamics); treeline; twentieth century; comparative study; ecosystem; geography; greenhouse effect; growth, development and aging; population dynamics; review; Russian Federation; species difference; tree; Ecosystem; Geography; Greenhouse Effect; Population Dynamics; Russia; Species Specificity; Trees; Eurasia; Coniferophyta",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., The Younger Dryas cold interval as viewed from central Greenland (2000) Quat. Sci. Rev, 19, pp. 213-226. , doi:10.1016/S0277- 3791(99)00062-1; Arctic Climate Impact Assessment 2004 Impacts of a warming Arctic: Arctic climate impact assessment. Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University PressBarber, V., Juday, G.P., Finney, B., Reduced growth of Alaska white spruce in the twentieth century from temperature-induced drought stress (2000) Nature, 405, pp. 668-672. , doi:10.1038/35015049; Berger, A., Loutre, M.F., Insolation values for the climate of the last 10 million years (1991) Quat. Sci. Rev, 10, pp. 297-317. , doi:10.1016/0277-3791(91)90033-Q; Bonan, G.B., Chapin, F.S., Thompson, S.L., Boreal forest and tundra ecosystems as components of the climate system (1995) Clim. Change, 29, pp. 145-167. , doi:10.1007/BF01094014; Briffa, K.R., Annual climate variability in the Holocene: Interpreting the message of ancient trees (2000) Quat. Sci. Rev, 19, pp. 87-105. , doi:10.1016/S0277-3791(99)00056-6; Briffa, K.R., Osborn, T.J., Seeing the wood from the trees (1999) Science, 284, pp. 926-927. , doi:10.1126/scien